latestPosts.caption:
People always said my parents to not allow me to dance just make her study and let her get married.

My love for dancing since childhood got me lot of compliments from family and friends as my expressions were too appealing and it motives me to get me into actions career. 

And so my acting journey started I didn’t have any experience or background in acting career I got it all from my father. Whatever I have learnt it’s all from My father he taught me everything.

I was born in middle class family in Vadodara Gujarat. Since I was 2 years old I started dancing I loved dancing and so my parents took me to dance classes I was really applaud for my dancing skills in school annuals, family functions and I won many dance competitions. 

My life took a turn when I got selected in India’s top 16 contestants in the show Boogie Woogie kids championship on 2012-13. For the first time we entered and saw Mumbai. Was all new for me, television shoot everything that I always imagined I was living the moment that time. Than I got selected in India’s Got talent season 7 While dancing everyone’s suggest to start acting as I was always appreciated with my expressions so we gave auditions and soon I got my first role.

And  later on I got a chance to work in a short film - Mukhagni. It all changed when I did my first big project for Colors Tv - Sasural Simar Ka as Anjali (simar’s daughter) and I did my episodics like savdhaan India, fear files… 

After completing my 12th boards i got show on Color’s Gujarati channel - Laxmi Sadaiv Mangalam as Shri Laxmi. 

The second project I did was a gujarati movie with  famous Gujarati Hero - Malhar Thakkar in movie - Gajab Thai Gayo as Paheli. I got selected for an OTT platform show - Aashiqana on Hotstar as Payal And while doing that I also got the show I’m doing right now - Saavi ki Savaari as Taashvi. 

Now, The ones who didn’t allowed us to dance, who always said my parents to not allow me to dance just make her study and let her get married are now praising us and also wanting there children to be like us.
